==Abstract==

This IIP describes the construction of compact block filters using Golomb-Rice coding. It is adapted from BIP 158 for INTcoin.

==Motivation==

Block filters allow light clients to efficiently determine if a block contains relevant transactions. Golomb-Rice coding provides near-optimal compression for the filter data.

==Specification==

===Basic Filter (Type 0)===

The basic filter contains:
* All scriptPubKeys of outputs created in the block
* All scriptPubKeys of outputs spent by inputs in the block

===Filter Construction===

# Collect all scripts to include
# Hash each script: <code>item = SipHash-2-4(k0, k1, script)</code>
# Sort hashed items
# Compute differences between consecutive items
# Encode differences using Golomb-Rice coding

===SipHash Key Derivation===

<pre>
key_data = SHA3-256(block_hash)
k0 = key_data[0:8] as uint64_le
k1 = key_data[8:16] as uint64_le
</pre>

===Golomb-Rice Parameters===

* P = 19 (parameter for Golomb-Rice coding)
* M = 784931 (M = 2^P * 1.497137)

===Filter Matching===

To check if a script matches:
<pre>
target = SipHash-2-4(k0, k1, script) % (N * M)
</pre>

Where N is the number of elements in the filter.

===INTcoin Adaptations===

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Component !! BIP 158 !! IIP-17
|-
| Key derivation hash || Double SHA256 || SHA3-256
|-
| Filter header hash || Double SHA256 || SHA3-256
|}

==Rationale==

===Why Golomb-Rice?===

* Near-optimal compression for sorted integer differences
* Simple to implement
* Fast encoding and decoding

===Why SipHash?===

* Fast hash function suitable for hash tables
* Keyed, preventing pre-computation attacks
* 64-bit output matches filter requirements

